{"title_page": "Ilaga", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Ilaga, Indonesia}}\n{{Infobox war faction\n| name         = Ilaga (ILONGGO LAND-GRABBERS ASSOCIATION\n| war          = [[Moro conflict]]\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| active       = 1971\u20131979 <br>2008\u2013present <small>(re-formed as 'New Ilaga')</small>\n| leaders      = Norberto Manero, Jr. <small>(formerly)</small>\n| headquarters = [[North Cotabato]]\n| area         = [[Mindanao]], [[Philippines]]\n| ideology     = [[Folk Catholicism]]\n| allies       = \n| opponents    = {{flagicon image|MNLF flag.svg}} [[Moro National Liberation Front]] <small>(until 1979)</small><br>{{flagicon|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} [[Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Fighters]]\n| url          = \n|active2=}}\n\nThe '''Ilaga''' ([[Visayan languages|Visayan]] for ''rat'', translated to mean Ilonggo landgrabbers)<ref name=\"pcijMindanaoMemoryOfMassacres\">{{cite web | last =Mariveles | first =Julius D. | title =Mindanao: A memory of massacres | url =http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres | accessdate =23 May 2016 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20160303043903/http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres | archive-date =3 March 2016 | url-status =dead }}</ref> is a [[Christian terrorism|Christian extremist]]<ref name=Ediger/><ref name=Dawn>{{cite web|title=Christian militia kills five Muslims in Philippines|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/908795/christian-militia-kills-five-muslims-in-philippines|publisher=Dawn|accessdate=21 March 2017|date=3 November 2008}}</ref> [[paramilitary]] group based in southern [[Philippines]]. The group is predominantly composed of [[Visayan people|Visayans]] (mostly [[Hiligaynon people|Ilonggo]]), embracing a form of [[Folk Catholicism]] that utilizes [[amulets]] and violence. \n\nThe group complemented the [[Philippine Constabulary]] as a militia force during the 1970s in southern [[Mindanao]] while fighting against [[Moro National Liberation Front|Moro]] guerrillas during the [[Moro insurgency in the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2013/09/28/1239187/anti-moro-group-resurfaces-ncotabato|title=Anti-Moro group resurfaces in NCotabato|work=philstar.com|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1970 to 1971 Ilaga launched a series of 21 massacres that left 518 people dead, 184 injured, and 243 houses burned down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres|title=Mindanao: A memory of massacres|date=2015-02-13|work=The PCIJ Blog|access-date=2018-03-10|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303043903/http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> The group committed one of its bloodiest acts with the [[Manili massacre]] on June 19, 1971, when the group killed 70<ref name=\"pcijMindanaoMemoryOfMassacres\" />\u201379<ref name=Arguillas/> [[Moro people|Moro]] civilians inside a [[mosque]].<ref name=\"atimes.com\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/EC06Ae03.html | title=The evolution of Philippine Muslim insurgency | author=Marco Garrido | work=[[Asia Times Online]] | date=March 6, 2003 | access-date=September 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Moro insurgency in the Philippines}}\n\nThe [[Mindanao]] region is rich in natural resources, including large quantities of mineral reserves. The [[Federal government of the United States|American]] colonial government and subsequently the [[Government of the Philippines|Philippine government]] pursued a policy of migration by resettling significant numbers of Christian Filipino settlers from the [[Visayas]] and [[Luzon]] onto tracts of land in Mindanao, beginning in the 1920s. This policy allowed Christian Filipinos to outnumber both the Moro and [[Lumad]] populations by the 1970s, which was a contributing factor in aggravating grievances between the Moro and Filipino Christian settlers as disputes over land increased. Another grievance by the Moro people is the extraction of Mindanao's natural resources by the [[Government of the Philippines|central government]] whilst many Moros continued to live in poverty.<ref name=Case>[http://manoa.hawaii.edu/ccpv/assets/docs/CCPV%20-%20The%20Bangsamoro%20Struggle%20for%20Self-Determination%20-%20A%20Case%20Study%20-%20By%20Caecilia%20Noble.pdf The Bangsamoro Struggle for Self-Determintation: A Case Study]</ref>\n\nThe Philippine government under [[Ferdinand Marcos]] encouraged [[Hiligaynon people|Ilonggo]] settlers who had emigrated to Mindanao to form a militia, which was eventually called the Ilaga. There is anecdotal evidence that the Ilaga often committed human rights abuses by targeting the Moro and Lumad peoples, as well as attempting to seize additional territory. The end result of Ilaga extremism is the lingering animosity between Moro and Christian communities. Mistrust and a cycle of violence are still felt today due to the creation of the Ilaga.<ref name=Case/>\n\n==History==\n\nFrom March 1970 to January 1972, the Ilaga committed 22 massacres resulting in the deaths of hundreds of [[Muslim]] civilians. The group is guilty of \"mutilat[ing] bodies of victims\" and \"marking bodies with a [[Christian cross|cross]].\" The group also burned down and looted many houses and properties.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Majul|first1=Cesar Adib|title=The Contemporary Muslim Movement in the Philippines|date=2015|publisher=BookBaby|isbn=9781483555584|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0d5eDQAAQBAJ|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Manili massacre===\n{{main|Manili massacre}}\nViolence attributed to the Ilaga reached its climax on June 19, 1971 with the Manili massacre of 70<ref name=\"pcijMindanaoMemoryOfMassacres\" />-79<ref name=Arguillas>{{cite news | last = Arguillas | first =Carolyn O. | title =De Lima: \"Oooops, sorry, it's Ampatuan Massacre not Maguindanao Massacre | publisher =MindaNews | date = 28 January 2010 | url =http://minda2010.timonera.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7546:-de-lima-oooops-sorry-its-ampatuan-massacre-not-maguindanao-massacre&catid=3:news&Itemid=50 | accessdate = 23 May 2016}}</ref> [[Moro people|Moro Muslims]] in a [[mosque]] in Manili, [[Carmen, Cotabato|Carmen]], [[North Cotabato]].<ref name=\"lar\">{{cite book | last =Larousse | first =William  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=qyo-Hti0-KAC&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=manili+massacre&source=bl&ots=s7kDGRWP_S&sig=07Hv__FHewh5pCDBc2_82lNF0pU&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=manili%20massacre&f=false | title = A Local Church Living for Dialogue: Muslim-Christian Relations in Mindanao-Sulu, Philippines 1965-2000| publisher =Gregorian Biblical BookShop | year =2001 | pages =136 | isbn =8876528792 }}</ref> The Muslim residents of the town had gathered in their mosque to participate in a supposed peace talk with [[Christians|Christian]] groups when a group of armed men dressed in uniforms similar to those worn by members of the [[Philippine Constabulary]] opened fire on them.<ref name=\"lar\"/>\n\n===1971 Battle of Lanao del Norte===\n\nFollowing the massacre at Manili, many [[Maranao people|Maranao]] Muslims fled to take shelter in the [[Lanao del Norte]]. Some Muslims formed small militant groups to counter the Ilaga. One such group was called the \"Barracudas\" and in September 1971, the Barracudas clashed with the Ilagas resulting in the deaths of hundreds of people on both sides of the conflict. The Ilagas also clashed with the Philippine Constabulary. The skirmishes continued until October, and over 60 Muslim houses were torched by the Ilaga.<ref name=Ediger>{{cite book|last1=Ediger|first1=Max|title=The Struggle in Mindanao|date=September 2001|publisher=Documentation for Action Groups in Asia|location=Matina Davao City, Philippines|page=14|url=http://www.daga.org.hk/dd/d2001/d109ph.pdf}}</ref><ref>Robert, B. McAmis, \"Muslim Filipinos 1970-1972,\" Solidarity 8, No. 2, February 1973, p. 7.</ref>\n\n===Post-2008 resurgence===\nIncreased tensions in the Philippines since 2008 have since seen the reemergence of the armed [[vigilante]] group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080829-157470/New-Ilaga-revives-fears-of-Mindanao-in-70s|title=New Ilaga revives fears of Mindanao in '70s|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107233548/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080829-157470/New-Ilaga-revives-fears-of-Mindanao-in-70s|archive-date=7 January 2009|accessdate=26 January 2015|url-status=dead}} http://cache1.asset-cache.net/gc/153307109-commander-max-stands-with-his-group-ilaga-a-gettyimages.jpg?v=1&c=IWSAsset&k=2&d=GkZZ8bf5zL1ZiijUmxa7QTpIrPwH16Bce0Gp83jTSVeIm4OGW2CKESx0ucvtWWoG {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924074501/http://cache1.asset-cache.net/gc/153307109-commander-max-stands-with-his-group-ilaga-a-gettyimages.jpg?v=1&c=IWSAsset&k=2&d=GkZZ8bf5zL1ZiijUmxa7QTpIrPwH16Bce0Gp83jTSVeIm4OGW2CKESx0ucvtWWoG |date=2016-09-24 }} http://nimg.sulekha.com/others/original700/2008-8-27-7-35-43-b3b9c446bc224beb90e3c8e3c21ecdc0-b3b9c446bc224beb90e3c8e3c21ecdc0-2.jpg{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> calling themselves the '''Bag-ong Ilaga''' (Visayan: ''New Ilaga'').<ref>[http://www.bulatlat.com/news/5-12/5-12-vigilante.htm \u201c2 New Vigilante Groups Surface in Mindanao\u201d] by Cheryll D. Fiel, Bulatlat Alipato Publications, retrieved September 14, 2008</ref> Since 2008, violence flared up with the [[Moro Islamic Liberation Front]] and the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] after the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines]] overruled the proposed treaty for an [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]].<ref name=WashP>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/13/AR2008091302274.html?nav=rss_world \u201cIn Philippines, Abandoned Deal Reignites Rebel War\u201d] by Blaine Harden, ''[[Washington Post]]'', retrieved September 14, 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/news/mindanao-civilians-under-threat-from-milf-units-and-militias-20080822 \u201cMindanao civilians under threat from MILF units and militias\u201d] [[Amnesty International]] August 22, 2008, retrieved September 14, 2008</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, the Ilaga killed five Muslim civilians in an ambush in Lanao del Norte.<ref name=Dawn/>\n\nIn 2012, two members of the group committed robbery and also murdered two people. They were then arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/region/2012/03/17/787655/inopacan-cops-nab-2-ilaga-gang-members|title=Inopacan cops nab 2 Ilaga Gang|website=philstar.com|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Moro insurgency in the Philippines]]\n* [[Moro people|Bangsamoro]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080912233008/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080901-157955/Ilaga-revival-to-make-things-worse--Piol  \u201cIlaga revival to make things worse \u2013 Pi\u00f1ol\u201d] [[Philippine Daily Inquirer]], retrieved September 14, 2008\n\n{{Moro conflict}}\n\n[[Category:Moro conflict]]\n[[Category:Paramilitary organizations based in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Hiligaynon people]]\n[[Category:Christian terrorism in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Ilaga, Indonesia}}\n{{Infobox war faction\n| name         = Ilaga\n| war          = [[Moro conflict]]\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| active       = 1971\u20131979 <br>2008\u2013present <small>(re-formed as 'New Ilaga')</small>\n| leaders      = Norberto Manero, Jr. <small>(formerly)</small>\n| headquarters = [[North Cotabato]]\n| area         = [[Mindanao]], [[Philippines]]\n| ideology     = [[Folk Catholicism]]\n| allies       = \n| opponents    = {{flagicon image|MNLF flag.svg}} [[Moro National Liberation Front]] <small>(until 1979)</small><br>{{flagicon|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} [[Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Fighters]]\n| url          = \n|active2=}}\n\nThe '''Ilaga''' ([[Visayan languages|Visayan]] for ''rat'', translated to mean Ilonggo landgrabbers)<ref name=\"pcijMindanaoMemoryOfMassacres\">{{cite web | last =Mariveles | first =Julius D. | title =Mindanao: A memory of massacres | url =http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres | accessdate =23 May 2016 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20160303043903/http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres | archive-date =3 March 2016 | url-status =dead }}</ref> is a [[Christian terrorism|Christian extremist]]<ref name=Ediger/><ref name=Dawn>{{cite web|title=Christian militia kills five Muslims in Philippines|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/908795/christian-militia-kills-five-muslims-in-philippines|publisher=Dawn|accessdate=21 March 2017|date=3 November 2008}}</ref> [[paramilitary]] group based in southern [[Philippines]]. The group is predominantly composed of [[Visayan people|Visayans]] (mostly [[Hiligaynon people|Ilonggo]]), embracing a form of [[Folk Catholicism]] that utilizes [[amulets]] and violence. \n\nThe group complemented the [[Philippine Constabulary]] as a militia force during the 1970s in southern [[Mindanao]] while fighting against [[Moro National Liberation Front|Moro]] guerrillas during the [[Moro insurgency in the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2013/09/28/1239187/anti-moro-group-resurfaces-ncotabato|title=Anti-Moro group resurfaces in NCotabato|work=philstar.com|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1970 to 1971 Ilaga launched a series of 21 massacres that left 518 people dead, 184 injured, and 243 houses burned down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres|title=Mindanao: A memory of massacres|date=2015-02-13|work=The PCIJ Blog|access-date=2018-03-10|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303043903/http://pcij.org/blog/2015/02/13/mindanao-a-memory-of-massacres|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> The group committed one of its bloodiest acts with the [[Manili massacre]] on June 19, 1971, when the group killed 70<ref name=\"pcijMindanaoMemoryOfMassacres\" />\u201379<ref name=Arguillas/> [[Moro people|Moro]] civilians inside a [[mosque]].<ref name=\"atimes.com\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/EC06Ae03.html | title=The evolution of Philippine Muslim insurgency | author=Marco Garrido | work=[[Asia Times Online]] | date=March 6, 2003 | access-date=September 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Moro insurgency in the Philippines}}\n\nThe [[Mindanao]] region is rich in natural resources, including large quantities of mineral reserves. The [[Federal government of the United States|American]] colonial government and subsequently the [[Government of the Philippines|Philippine government]] pursued a policy of migration by resettling significant numbers of Christian Filipino settlers from the [[Visayas]] and [[Luzon]] onto tracts of land in Mindanao, beginning in the 1920s. This policy allowed Christian Filipinos to outnumber both the Moro and [[Lumad]] populations by the 1970s, which was a contributing factor in aggravating grievances between the Moro and Filipino Christian settlers as disputes over land increased. Another grievance by the Moro people is the extraction of Mindanao's natural resources by the [[Government of the Philippines|central government]] whilst many Moros continued to live in poverty.<ref name=Case>[http://manoa.hawaii.edu/ccpv/assets/docs/CCPV%20-%20The%20Bangsamoro%20Struggle%20for%20Self-Determination%20-%20A%20Case%20Study%20-%20By%20Caecilia%20Noble.pdf The Bangsamoro Struggle for Self-Determintation: A Case Study]</ref>\n\nThe Philippine government under [[Ferdinand Marcos]] encouraged [[Hiligaynon people|Ilonggo]] settlers who had emigrated to Mindanao to form a militia, which was eventually called the Ilaga. There is anecdotal evidence that the Ilaga often committed human rights abuses by targeting the Moro and Lumad peoples, as well as attempting to seize additional territory. The end result of Ilaga extremism is the lingering animosity between Moro and Christian communities. Mistrust and a cycle of violence are still felt today due to the creation of the Ilaga.<ref name=Case/>\n\n==History==\n\nFrom March 1970 to January 1972, the Ilaga committed 22 massacres resulting in the deaths of hundreds of [[Muslim]] civilians. The group is guilty of \"mutilat[ing] bodies of victims\" and \"marking bodies with a [[Christian cross|cross]].\" The group also burned down and looted many houses and properties.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Majul|first1=Cesar Adib|title=The Contemporary Muslim Movement in the Philippines|date=2015|publisher=BookBaby|isbn=9781483555584|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0d5eDQAAQBAJ|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Manili massacre===\n{{main|Manili massacre}}\nViolence attributed to the Ilaga reached its climax on June 19, 1971 with the Manili massacre of 70<ref name=\"pcijMindanaoMemoryOfMassacres\" />-79<ref name=Arguillas>{{cite news | last = Arguillas | first =Carolyn O. | title =De Lima: \"Oooops, sorry, it's Ampatuan Massacre not Maguindanao Massacre | publisher =MindaNews | date = 28 January 2010 | url =http://minda2010.timonera.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7546:-de-lima-oooops-sorry-its-ampatuan-massacre-not-maguindanao-massacre&catid=3:news&Itemid=50 | accessdate = 23 May 2016}}</ref> [[Moro people|Moro Muslims]] in a [[mosque]] in Manili, [[Carmen, Cotabato|Carmen]], [[North Cotabato]].<ref name=\"lar\">{{cite book | last =Larousse | first =William  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=qyo-Hti0-KAC&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=manili+massacre&source=bl&ots=s7kDGRWP_S&sig=07Hv__FHewh5pCDBc2_82lNF0pU&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=manili%20massacre&f=false | title = A Local Church Living for Dialogue: Muslim-Christian Relations in Mindanao-Sulu, Philippines 1965-2000| publisher =Gregorian Biblical BookShop | year =2001 | pages =136 | isbn =8876528792 }}</ref> The Muslim residents of the town had gathered in their mosque to participate in a supposed peace talk with [[Christians|Christian]] groups when a group of armed men dressed in uniforms similar to those worn by members of the [[Philippine Constabulary]] opened fire on them.<ref name=\"lar\"/>\n\n===1971 Battle of Lanao del Norte===\n\nFollowing the massacre at Manili, many [[Maranao people|Maranao]] Muslims fled to take shelter in the [[Lanao del Norte]]. Some Muslims formed small militant groups to counter the Ilaga. One such group was called the \"Barracudas\" and in September 1971, the Barracudas clashed with the Ilagas resulting in the deaths of hundreds of people on both sides of the conflict. The Ilagas also clashed with the Philippine Constabulary. The skirmishes continued until October, and over 60 Muslim houses were torched by the Ilaga.<ref name=Ediger>{{cite book|last1=Ediger|first1=Max|title=The Struggle in Mindanao|date=September 2001|publisher=Documentation for Action Groups in Asia|location=Matina Davao City, Philippines|page=14|url=http://www.daga.org.hk/dd/d2001/d109ph.pdf}}</ref><ref>Robert, B. McAmis, \"Muslim Filipinos 1970-1972,\" Solidarity 8, No. 2, February 1973, p. 7.</ref>\n\n===Post-2008 resurgence===\nIncreased tensions in the Philippines since 2008 have since seen the reemergence of the armed [[vigilante]] group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080829-157470/New-Ilaga-revives-fears-of-Mindanao-in-70s|title=New Ilaga revives fears of Mindanao in '70s|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107233548/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080829-157470/New-Ilaga-revives-fears-of-Mindanao-in-70s|archive-date=7 January 2009|accessdate=26 January 2015|url-status=dead}} http://cache1.asset-cache.net/gc/153307109-commander-max-stands-with-his-group-ilaga-a-gettyimages.jpg?v=1&c=IWSAsset&k=2&d=GkZZ8bf5zL1ZiijUmxa7QTpIrPwH16Bce0Gp83jTSVeIm4OGW2CKESx0ucvtWWoG {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924074501/http://cache1.asset-cache.net/gc/153307109-commander-max-stands-with-his-group-ilaga-a-gettyimages.jpg?v=1&c=IWSAsset&k=2&d=GkZZ8bf5zL1ZiijUmxa7QTpIrPwH16Bce0Gp83jTSVeIm4OGW2CKESx0ucvtWWoG |date=2016-09-24 }} http://nimg.sulekha.com/others/original700/2008-8-27-7-35-43-b3b9c446bc224beb90e3c8e3c21ecdc0-b3b9c446bc224beb90e3c8e3c21ecdc0-2.jpg{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> calling themselves the '''Bag-ong Ilaga''' (Visayan: ''New Ilaga'').<ref>[http://www.bulatlat.com/news/5-12/5-12-vigilante.htm \u201c2 New Vigilante Groups Surface in Mindanao\u201d] by Cheryll D. Fiel, Bulatlat Alipato Publications, retrieved September 14, 2008</ref> Since 2008, violence flared up with the [[Moro Islamic Liberation Front]] and the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] after the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines]] overruled the proposed treaty for an [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]].<ref name=WashP>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/13/AR2008091302274.html?nav=rss_world \u201cIn Philippines, Abandoned Deal Reignites Rebel War\u201d] by Blaine Harden, ''[[Washington Post]]'', retrieved September 14, 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/news/mindanao-civilians-under-threat-from-milf-units-and-militias-20080822 \u201cMindanao civilians under threat from MILF units and militias\u201d] [[Amnesty International]] August 22, 2008, retrieved September 14, 2008</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, the Ilaga killed five Muslim civilians in an ambush in Lanao del Norte.<ref name=Dawn/>\n\nIn 2012, two members of the group committed robbery and also murdered two people. They were then arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.p